This paper analyzes linguistic complexity and its relationship with scientific impact in the fields of Biology and Psychology. The use of linguistic features as a proxy for scientific writing suggests a focus on natural language processing (NLP) techniques, which is a common theme in the sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). Additionally, the analysis of scientific impact suggests a potential interest in machine learning (cs.LG) and information retrieval (cs.IR) techniques. The use of full-text articles also suggests a potential interest in deep learning (cs.DL) techniques for text analysis. Finally, the interdisciplinary nature of the study, which combines linguistic analysis with scientific impact analysis, suggests a potential interest in the sub-category of cybernetics (cs.CY).
